{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937113001/0486.xml":{"full_text":"EXCHANGE CLUB\ni SCORES POLICE\n\nCriticizes Attitude of Au\nthorities Toward Driv\ners of Private Cars\nf 1\nThe Waterbury Exchange club\nmade tentative plans last night to\ncorrect what they termed \u201cWater*\nbury\u2019s unsatisfactory center traffic\ncondition.\u201d\nSupt. of Police William J. Roach\nand other police officials were\nhighly surprised today at the\nDR. JOHN B. FRENEY\nPresident\ncharges made at a meeting of the\nExchange club that \u201cpatrolmen In\nthe center vicinity are guilty of nu\nmerous discourtesies In handling\ntraffic and not allowing drivers of\nprivate cars any opportunity to stop\nand shop In the stores.\u201d\nWith Dr. John B. Freney, presi\ndent of the club presiding, the club\nattacked the policy of the police\ndepartment, In \"allowing so much\nspace about the center for bus stops\nand leaving none for the drivers of\nprivate cars.\u201d\nFurther discussion of the situa\ntion will be sponsored by the Ex\nchange club at future meeting such\nas that held last night in the Press\nclub. It is apparent that a set of\nrecommendations will be drafted\nand presented to civic officials. The\nrecommendations will be designed\nto remedy the \"unsatisfactory con\ndition.\u201d No committee of the club\nhas been named to carry out the\nstudy planned.\nALLEN OBSERVING\n20TH ANNIVERSARY\nPopular District Manager\nEntered C. L. P. Co.\nService in 1917\nCharles J. Allen, manager of the\nWaterbury district of the Connec\nticut Light Power Co., today cele\nbrated the 20th anniversary of his\nfirst association with the concern.\nEmployes of the Waterbury district\npresented him with flowers and a\ntraveling bag, together with a card\nof congratulations signed by 366\npersons, the entire district personnel.\nMr. Allen Joined the Connecticut\nLight Power Co. Nov. 30,1917, and\nwas first assigned to the post of of\nfice manager at New Britain. A few\nmonths later. In March, 1918. he\ncame to Waterbury as chief cleric\na i>d auditor. Since that time, with\nthe exception of three years spent In\nthe Hartford office, he has been sta\ntioned In Waterbury.\nIn December, 1929 after the merger\nof the local light and gas companies\nMr. Allen was made manager of the\njoint office for the district.\nThe territory under his charge In\ncludes Waterbury Naugatuck, Sey\nmour, Middlebury, Southbury, Ox\nford, Monroe, Wolcott, Watertown,\nBeacon Palls, Bethany and Wood\nbury.\nMr. Allen came to Connecticut\nfrom Providence, R. I., where he was\nIn the employ of the Narragansett\nElectric Co. He served'as chief ac\ncountant at Shartenberg\u2019s, New Ha\nven, before joining the light com\npany.\nHe is a member of the Waterbury\nlodge of Elks, the Rotary club, the\nWaterbury club, the Waterbury\nChamber of Commerce and a num\nber of trade organizations.\nY.M.C.A. Notes\nThe Y. M. C. A. Christian Edu\ncation Committee at Its meeting last\nnight endorsed the following pro\n8lYoung Men's Clubs\u2014Program,\nLeadership, Leadership Training,\nRace Relations, Brotherhood Jew\nand Christian; World Peace, Per\nsonal Counsel, Sunday Fonuns,\nLenten Season, Y. M. C. A. Inter\nnational, Church Cooperation, Com\nmunity Cooperation.\nSub-committees which will carry\non their special phases of the pro\ngram have been set up In each of\nthe divisions.\nDr. Mllllcent Pond spoke of the\nwork In Leadership Training under\ntaken by the Advisors\u2019 Association.\nHoward E. Coe and Arthur Dubois\ncommented on the plan of securing\nleadership. Chase Kimball, chair\nman of the committee spoke of\nthe work the YMCA la doing Inter\nnationally, particularly In China In\nconnection with refugee camps.\nThe committee wlH hold Its next\nmeeting In January.\nCommons Club.\nThe Commpns.club of the Central\nY M. O. A. will sponsor a lobby\nforum tomorrow night at 7 on\n\u201cDiesel Engines\u201d. The subject will\nbe presented In the form of motion\npictures accompanied by descriptive\nremarks by a representative of the\nHemphill Diesel Engine Co.\nFred J. Dempsey, chairman of the\nprogram committee of the Com\nmons club will preside. The public\nIs Invited.\nEX-NEWS HAWK\nDale Van Every, now readying the\nicrlpt of Paramount\u2019s \u201cSpawn of\njie North,\" adaptation of Barrett\nRWloughy\u2019s novel of pirate flsher\nnen. formerly was a natlonl execu\ntive of a great news servtoe (Dnlted\ni),\nRed Cross Roll Call\nTo Reach $8,000 Mark\nReceipts of the annual local Red\n'Cross Roll Call were further in\ncreased today when additional re\nturns sent the total to over 97,000.\nApproximately $600 was received\nsince yesterday.\nAdditional returns are still com\ning In, and the total is expected to\nreach $9,000 or more before final\nfigures are tabulated.\nReturns to date are as follows:\nPreviously acknowledged: 96,\n517.89; American Brass Co, Miss\nDorothy M. Cole, $155.60; American\nMetal Hose, Ted Parker, $54.25;\nFrench Mfg. Co, Mr. Rogers, $32;\nElton hotel, Vincent Oerardl, $13.26;\nCharles F. Kenworthy, Inc, Miss\nBarbara Kenworthy, $9; Patent\nButton Co, Frank Driscoll, $24;\nRoot Boyd, Inc, $6; Soufhmayd\nHome, $18; Waterbury Police de\npartment (additional), Capt. Dug\ngan, $1; Waterbury National Bank\nBldg, Mrs. A. Henry Welsman, $3;\nWaterbury National Bank booth,\nMrs. A. Henry Weisman, *18.95;\nCity Hall, Mrs. Selina Samaha, *4\n(additional); Woodruff St., Mrs. R.\nB. Hayes, *15; Momlngslde Ave.,\nMrs. J. Palen, *8; Conlston Ave.,\nMrs. Carter, *36; Tremont, Sudbury\nSts, Mrs. Robert Liddell, *4AO;\nSteuben St., Grandview Ave, from\nEconomy to Robbins St, Miss Bar*\nbara Doherty, $15; Windsor St, Mrs.\nA. N. Oolgrove, *33; Watertown\nAve, from Irvington to 1391, Miss\nMarguerite Dick, *8; Irvington ave\nnue, Wlllowdale, Irvington place,\nMrs. E. W. Wallace, *10; West Main\nSt. from Colley to Junction, Miss\nAnne Savage, *5; Watervllle St, No.\n370 to 776, Mrs. R. Rangoon, *3.50:\nWatervllle St, No. 6 to 60, Mrs.\nEarl McCann, *11; Southbury and\nSouth Britain branch, Milton E.\nCoer, chairman, *66.35; Ladles\u2019\nMontagnese auxiliary, *3; mall sub\nscriptions, *5; office subscriptions,\n*5.\nTotals returns to date: *7,059.55.\n-SPOTLIGHTING\nBrass City News\nTriple Crash\nTwo men were arrested on\ncharges of motor vehicle law vio\nlations yesterday following a col\nlision Involving three cars, only\none of which was damaged to any\nextent. The collision took place\non Central avenue, Involving cars\nowned by Mrs. Margaret S. Kay?\nnor, of 194 Buckingham avenue,\nNlcholasLaCarpa, 28, of 133 Chase\navenue, and Thomas F. Kearney,\n44. of VI Chambers street.\nLaCapra was arrested on a\ncharge of reckless driving and\nKearney was charged with viola\ntion of the rules of the road.\nThe Kaynor car was parked, and\nwas strcck after the other two\ncars collided. Motor Patrolmen\nOene Dohetry and Joseph Mc\nCarthy Investigated.\nLeg fractured\nStruck last night by a car op\nerated by John D. MacDonald,\n20, of 14 Bowers street, Water\ntown, Richard Johnson, 48, col\nored of 34 French street sustain\ned a fractured leg. He was treated\nat the office of Dr. Harold E.\nMorrill, assistant medical exami\nner.\nThe accident took place at 8\no\u2019clock on West Main near State\nstreet. No arrest was made, pend\ning further Investigation. Sergt.\nJoseph McEvoy and Motor Patrol\nman Thomas Redding are In\ncharge.\nAnti-Semitism\nCharles Rosengarten, state pres\nident of the American Jewish con\ngress, of which Rudolph Hennlck\nis local president, Aaron D. Solo\nmon and Samuel Kramer, were\ndelegates Sunday to a congress at\nWashington, D. C\u201e where mes\nsages denouncing aptl-Semltlsm\nwere heard from 80 senators and\n22 governors. The officials urged\na united front In Europe and\nAmerica against anti-Semitism.\n\u201cCritical\u201d\n...Authorities at St. Mary's hoa-.\n.pltal reported today that the con\ndition of Mrs. Bertha Linteau, 35\nof 11 West Clay street. Is \"critical.\"\nThe woman was injured Sunday\nnight in an automobile accident on\nMeriden road. Her husband, the\ndriver of the car. Is being held as a\ncoroner\u2019s prisoner, pending the re\nsult of her injuries.\nNovena Opens\nA novena In honor of the Im\nmauclate Conception will begin\ntonight at the Church of the Im\nmaculate Conception, with serv\nices continuing each evening at\n7:30 p. m. The novena will close\nDec. 8, the Feast of the Immacu\nlate Conception.\nServices will be conducted by\nRev. James Halligan, C. M\u201e well\nknown to Waterbury Catholics.\nThe Novena is open to all, and\nlarge dally attendances are ex\npected.\nUNGREATFUL DOG!\nGeorges Rigaud, the handsome\nArgentine whom Paramount will\npresent in \u201cMidnight\u201d opposite Ca\nrole Lombard, for his American de\nbut, moved out of the Beverly-Wll\nshlre hotel Into a house In Beverly\nHills to keep his dog from fretting.\nBut the animal bit the first caller\nwho tried to pet him, and now has\nbeen taken away by the dog catcher\nfor ten days\u2019 quarantine I\nDeserted\nDesertion is charged in the\nsuit for divorce entered today by\nJoseph Lombard against Joyce\nOrlowskl Lombard, both ot Water\nbury, in the superior court.\nThe couple were married Nov. 1,\n1933 and the alleged dessertion\ntook place July 3, 1934. There is\na three-year-old child.\nFrancis J. Summa is counsel for\nthe plaintiff.\nLiquor Law!\nTwo alleged liquor law violators\nwere given continuances to Dec.\n14 when they were arraigned be\nfore Judge John F. McGrath In\ncity court today.\nBenjamin Shlmkus, 21 of 561\nNorth Riverside street is'charged\nwith selling liquor on Sunday.\nCharles Fltspatrick, 39, of 1679\nEast Main street, is charged with\nselling before hours.\nChimney Fire\nFiremen from Engines 1 and 7\nand Truck 3 were forced today to\nrip the entire chimney from a\nhouse at 1000 North Main street.\nThe house is owned by Lucy De\nJohn and accupled by Frank Di\nBlasl.\nThe fire started in the chimney\nat a point where an obsolete fire\nplace had been covered with beav\nerboard. Damages was kept to a\nminimum. Companies answered\nthe alarm at 10:02 a. m. and re\nturned forty-eight mln'utes later.\nNLRB ELECTION\nHERE TOMORROW\nChase Rolling Mills Em\nployes to Decide on Col\nlective Agency\nFour hundred and forty-one em\nployes of the North Main street roll\ning mills of the Chase Brass\nCopper companies were found\neligible to vote In the NLRB elec\ntion which will be conducted tomor\nrow, after a thorough check of the\npayroll by officials of the company\nand the Brass Workers union yes\nterday afternoon.\nOfficials of the union were closet\ned with Fred A. Jackie, works man\nager of the company yesterday af\nternoon for the check of the pay\nroll.\nBallots Distributed\nSample ballots and notices of the\nelection, which have been supplied\nby the government, were distributed\nyesterday and today among the\nworkers of the mill. At the request\nof the union they were printed in\nItalian as well as in English.\nThe election will be held between\nthe hours of 11 a. m., and 3 p. m\u201e\ntomorrow at booths which have been\nset up In the garage building of\nthe North Main street plant. Allen\nJ. MacAdams, representative of the\nNLRB will supervise the procedure.\nFour checkers, two representing\nthe union and two v acting on be\nhalf of the company, will be seated\nat the entrance to the polls, check\ning off each employe who votes.\nThey will be identified by the four\ncheckers, who also will double-check\nby determining the voters factory\nnumber.\nProcedure\nAll equipment for the election has\nbeen supplied by the government\nThe procedure of the election will\nallow for a man to appear at the\npolls, be identified, receive a bal\nlot and advance to a booth where\nhe will answer the question. \"Do\nyou want the Brass Workers Union\nto represent you in all collective\nbargaining?\" The answer will be\na simple \"yes\" or \u201cno\u201d. He will then\nfold his ballot and place it Into the\nbox which will be under the super\nvision of Mr. MacAdams.\nUnion officials today announced\na mass meeting of all employes of\nthe North Main street mill of the\nChase Brass Copper company, to\nbe held tonight at 8 o'clock in the\nSpencer avenue headquarters. All\nemployes, union members or not,\nhave been invited. Final Instruc\ntions and Information pertaining to\nthe election will be imparted.\nA meeting of the Clock Shop em\nployes will also be held In head\nquarters tonight at 8 o\u2019clock. The\nexecutive board of the union will\nmeet at 7:30 tonight.\nFRATERNAL NEWS\nTownsend Lodge\nGrand Deputy Randall C. Frink\nwas the speaker last night dur\ning a supper held following the\nregular meeting of Townsend\nlodge, Order of Odd Fellows, an\nevent held at the quarters of the\nlocal chapter. During the meeting\nthe third degree of the lodge was\nconferred upon five candidates,\nRANDALL C. FRINK\nGrand Deputy\ntwo of whom are now associated\nwith the Hartford chapter. J.\nWilliam Gardner, district deputy\nwas In charge of ceremonies, and\nthe exercises were conducted by\nthe Hartford degree team.\nThe first or Initiatory degree\nwill be conferred at a meeting to\nm mi i\nHOLD EVERYTHING!\nI 1\n\u201cWhat\u2019ll we do\ni\neat him, or send a message?\u201d\ntake place next Monday night\nwith exercises by the Nosahogan\nlodge degree team.\nEuclid Lodge\nIdris R. Alderson worshipful\nmaster of Euclid lodge, Order of\nMasons, will preside at a com\nbined meeting of Continental,\nHarmony, Euclid and Liberty\nlodges which take place tonight at\n8 o'clock at Masonic temple. The\nmeeting has been called for the\npurpose of conferring the master\nMason degree, exercises to be ex\nemplified by offleers of the four\nlodges.\nPrincipal parts will be taken by\nMr. Alderson, Oordon C. Sper\nrlng, master of Harmony; Edward\nD. Helnman, master of Liberty,\nand H. LeRoy Woodcock, master\nof Continental. Refreshments\nwill be served later in the evening\nand all Masons In Waterbury and\nthe vicinity are Invited to be in\nattendance.\nIrish-Americans\nArrangements will be completed\ntonight for a smoker which will\nbe sponsored by the Irlsh-Amerl\ncan Social club tomorrow night\nat V. P. W. hall. Tonight\u2019s meet\ning will be held at 39 Field street.\nAttorney Hugh McOlll, president\nof the club, is chairman of the ar\nrangements committee.\nFrigentina Society\nA large attendance was present\nlast night at the annual harvest\ndance of the Frigentina auxiliary,\nheld at Speedwell hall. Offleers of\nthe chapter will be elected at the\nnext meeting, December 13th, and\nplans completed for a Christmas\nparty.\nThe committee in charge of ar\nrangements for the successful\ndance of last night includes: Mrs.\nMlldrfed Famigllttl, Miss Anna\nDavlno, Miss Joan Pugllese, Miss\nMargaret Oalo, Mrs. Rachel Clrel\nlo, and Mrs. Glovannina Oenova.\nMAY SETTLE BUS\nSTRIKE SHORTLY\nCleveland, Nov. 30.\u2014(UP)\u2014Fed\neral Conciliator John L. Connor re\nported \"definite progress\" today in\nefforts to settle a strike of Grey\nhound bus drivers while company\nofficials ordered strikers to return\nto work before noon tomorrow or\n\u201cbe considered as having resigned\nfrom the company\".\nConnor will resume negotiations\nwith Ivan Bowen, Greyhound attor\nney, and T. J. McGrath, counsel for\nthe Brotherhood of Railway Train\nmen, which called the strike in a\n16-state area last week to enforce\ndemands for higher wages and a\nclosed shop. The federal mediator\nsaid that both sides were \"showing\nfine cooperation\".\nThe ultimatum to the strikers,\nrepresenting the position of the\neight companies affected by the\nstrike, was distributed with copies\nof a contract acceptable to the\nmanagement. It proposed a wage\nincrease of one-fourth cent per mile.\nThe union demanded a boost from\n3.16 to 5.5 cents per mile, with a\nminimum guarantee of 300 miles a\nday.\nViolence In scattered sections of\nJlte strike arwyxmtlnued.\nThe British Post Office depart\nment will employe 75,000 extra men\nto nandle Christmas malls.\nHe\u2019s Santa\u2019s \u201cLittle Helper*\n1 I' IIHh\"\u00ab\"ll I\u2014\u2014\u2014 i I\nSanta Clans mar be working like a beaver in his toy shop 'way np in\nthe frozen north, but he\u2019d never ret all the Christmas stockings filled\nwithout help from Are and police station \u201csub-workshops\u201d like the one\nshown above. Big, tough cops and Are laddies all over the nation are\naccommodatinr clumsy Angers to the delicate task of renovating dolls,\ntrains, teddy bears and tricycles of yesteryear to gladden the hearts of\nneedy children whom Santa might forget.\nEvery Effort To Check\nBusiness Recession\nMore Generous Attitude Developed By Federal Govt.;\nCapital Gains, Corporation Surplus Taxes Must Go\nBy LYLE C. WILSON\n(United Press SUIT Correspondent)\nWashington, Nov. 30\u2014(UP)\u2014Fed\neral efforts to check the business\nrecession developed a more generous\nattitude today toward tax revision\nto aid business and a concrete ap\nplication of treasury economy plans\nNo Samples?\nPemberton Street Man\nHas Neighbor Ar\nrested for Self\nService in\nWine Cellar\nThe next time Arthur Hotch\nkiss of 13 Pemberton street gets a\nyen for wine he won\u2019t quench it\nby drinking wine from the cellar\nof Salvatore Leopezzo. For Mr.\nLeopezzo has hts wine kegs meas\nured and hts wine bottles counted\nand when It started to diminish\nhe wanted to know the reason why.\nHe claims he found it when he\naccused his neighbor, Mr. Hotch\nkiss. and then had him arrested\nby Patrolmen Joseph Delaney and\nJohn Walsh who served a warrant\nlast night.\nIn city court this morning Mr,\nLeopezzo told Judge John F. Mc\nGrath that at least $2 worth of\nwine had disappeared, presumably\ndue to the work and thirst of\nneighbor Hotchkiss. Judge Mc\nGrath continued the case until\nSaturday, December 4.\nHigh School\nNotes\nGirls\u2019 Athletic Association\nThe fifth and final game of the\nSee-Gee soccer tournament was\nheld In the gym on Monday after\nnoon. The contest proved a very\nexciting upset when the Super-Sox\ndefeated the Zip-Kicks for the first\ntime, the score being 37-14.\nThe Zip-Kicks are the winners\nof the tournament, having won 4\ngames to the one of the Super-Sox.\nThe members of the teams are\nas follows:\nZip-Kicks\nCaptain Phyllis Anderson, Assis\ntant Captain Dora Eurell, Stella\nZornlck, Rose DeLeon, Mary Keefe,\nMargaret Connor, Alyce Canning,\nRita Palmerini, Lillian Solomon,\nCorlnne Hlckox, Marlon Rlslk, Shir\nley Harper, Bertha Welte, Dorothy\nMcCowen, Ann Berry, Muriel Mos\nkowltz, Jennie Coporaso, Ruth\nMiller.\nSuper-Sox\nCaptain Doris Lange, Assistant\nCaptain Virginia Tappln. Jacque\nline Yavecchia, Ruth Kastleman,\nCelesta Petrlllo, Mildred Wills,\nMary Rlszuto, Mary Oyba, Cynthia\nRlttenband, Betty Cowperthwait,\nEvelyn Kustls, Thelma Connor,\nJuanita Reynolds, Nancy Barlow,\nOladys Claps, Mary Joyce, Florence\nOreenblatt.\nThe basetball tournament begins\non Monday. All girls who are inter\nested are invited to Join.\nMiss Florence Turnbull is instruc\ntor and advisor of the group.\nDramatic Club\nThe next meeting of the Crosby\nSenior Dramatic Club will take\nplace tonight at 7 o\u2019clock in the\nAssembly Hall with Miss Marie\nMcDonald, faculty advisor as direc\ntor.\nOccupations Club\nMembers of the Occupations Club\nheld a meeting at the close of the\nschool session today at which time\nplans were formulated for a moving\npicture show to take place on Fri\nday,\nGlee Club\nThe combined High Schools Glee\nClub held a regular rehearsal last\nnight at the Crosby Assembly Hall.\nRECONSTRUCT PALACE\nThe United States presidential\npalace built in 1879, the cornerstone\nof which Capt. Edwin F. Locke of\nthe U. 8. engineers is now seeking,\nwill be seen in Cecil B. DeMllle\u2019s\n\u201cThe Bucaneer,\u201d starring Fredrlc\nMarch. It has been reconstructed\nauthentically for, the film.\nto balance the budget.\nChairman Pat Harrison of the\nsenate finance committee repudi\nated present capital gains and cor\nporation surplus taxes in a speech\ninsisting that both must be modi\nfied.\nHarrison gave business grounds to\nhope that modification may go be\nyond limits now planned by'house\nways and means committeemen.\nThe senator charged the taxes with\nresponsibility for curtailing federal\nrevenue'retarding industrial devel\nopment and contributing to unem\nployment. He said the capital gains\ntax had discouraged trading In\nstocks, securities and other hold\nings.\nDetails of Balancing\nDetails of budget balancing econ\nomies to be eected by reducing fed\neral contributions to highway con\nstruction were contained In a presi\ndential message to congress to be\nread shortly after noon.\nPresident Roosevelt outlined gen\neral highway economy objectives\nlast week before departing for a\nFlorida fishing vacation. It was\nunderstood the administration\nhoped to modfy statutory require\nments that more than $200,000,000\nof highway funds be offered annu\nally as federal grants In aid of road\nbuilding. On the basis of last week\u2019s\nWhite House remarks It was esti\nmated that the president might ask\ncongress to reduce that commitment\nto $80,000,000 or $90,000,000 to es\ntablish a net saving of upwards of\n$100,000,000.\nEndorses Economy\nMr. Roosevelt\u2019s message repre\nsents a positive endorsement of the\neconomy program proposed Nov. 10\nIn a speech by Secretary of Treas\nury Henry Morgenthau, Jr. Mor\ngenthau told a New York audience\nthe government should bring Its ex\npenditures within income by mak\ning cuts aggregating $700,000,000 In\nappropriation for unemployment\nrelief, Civilian Conservation corps,\npublic highways, public works and\nagriculture.\nThose Items of expenditure will\naggregate $3,311,000,000 in this fis\ncal year. Morgenthau\u2019s proposed\neconomies would reduce the cost\nnext year to $2,611,000,000. Congres\nsional reaction to economics In the\nfields proposed by Morgenthau still\nIs uncertain but there is general\nnon-partisan enthusiasm for a re\nduction of taxes that apply to bus\niness.\nnHrriBun issues narums\nHarrison warned In a radio ad\ndress last night that \"people should\nnot be encouraged to expect a retro\nactive feature\" in modification of\neither the corporation surplus or\ncapital gains levies.\n\"Every good citizen,\" lie said, \"will\nappreciate that adequate taxes must\nbe provided for the efficient admin\nistration of government. Only In\nexceptional cases should the pur\npose be of a social or punitive na\nture. I have no doubt that the\ncountry today Is suering from fear\nand uncertainty, occasioned, may I\nsay, to some extent by certain pro\nvisions of our tax laws.\n\u201cAt the prfesent time, I believe\nwe have at least two so-called abil\nity-to-pay taxes which have reached\na point of diminishing rather than\nIncreasing revenues. The taxes to\nwhich I refer are the undistributed\nprofits tax and the tax on capital\ngains. Not only do I believe that\nthese taxes have an adverse eect\nso far as revenue Is concerned, but\nI believe they have retarded Indus\ntrial progress and contributed to\nthe unemployment situation.\u201d\nCorrect Mistakes\nHarrison Insisted that when a\npublic servant makes a mistake\n\"then the mistake should be ac\nknowledged and corrected\u201d. He said\nthat large corporations should not\nbe permitted to build up unreason\nable and unnecessary reserves but\nargued that It Is a \u201charsh and un\nwise policy for the government to\ncompel a corporation that may be\ngiving employment to hundreds of\nthousands of men and women to\ndeclare its earnings In the form of\ndividends to it* stockholders when\nIt needs such earnings to perpetuate\nthe employment of those people.\n\u201cIt Is my hope and belief,\u201d he\ncontinued, \u201cthat In any event the\nlaw will be modified so as to permit\na corporation, if It desires, to pay\nfrom Its annual earnings, without\npenalty, amounts for debt retire\nment and for business expansion.\"\nLATE REALTY NEWS\nMortgage Release\nMargaret Haase to John and\nAnna Herbasnk.\niA\nMarket Opens Steady\nAfter Drop Of Monday\nVolume Was Very Light\u2014Bonds Firmed Up\u2014Cotton\nEased Off\u2014Changes in All Issues Fractional\nBY ELMER C. WALZER\n(United Press FinsneUI Editor)\nNew York, Nov. 30.\u2014(UP)\u2014The\nstock market opened steady today\nafter a decline yesterday. Volume\nwas light. Bonds firmed while cot\nton eased 3 to 7 points.\nAllied Chemical gained a point to\n155 and eBthlehem Steel was up 1\nat 50. Otherwise deviations from\nthe previous close were fractional.\nUnited States Steel opened at\n54 3-8 up 5-8; General Motors 35\nup 1-8; Chrysler 57 1-2 up 1-8;\nConsolidated Edison 27 3-8 up 3-8;\nMontgomery Ward 35 1-2 up 1-8;\nKennecott 35 1-4 up 1-2 and Stand\n1:15 P. M. PRICES\nWHITEHOUSE CO.\nAllied Chem. 155\nAm. Can 85\nAm. Sm. Ref. 48%\nAm. Tel. Tel. 148%\nAnaconda Cop. 30 Vi\nAtch. Top. 8. P. 39%\nBalt Ohio 12%\nBeth. Steel 51%\nBorden 17%\nCan. Pacific 8%\nCase Mach. 92%\nChes. Ohio 38%\nChrysler Motor 58%\nConsolidated Oil. 27%\nCon. Edison 27\nContinental Can. 43 Vi\nCom Products No Open\nDuPont. 109%\nEastman Kodak 150%\nElec. Auto-Lite 20%\nFreeport Texas 23\nGeneral Elec. 42%\nGeneral Foods. 30%\nGeneral Motors 36 V4\nGoodyear 21%\nInt\u2019l. Tel. Tel. 7\nJohns Manville 80Vi\nKennecot Cop. 35%\nKresge Stores 16 Vi\nKroger Groceries 16%\nLambert Chem. No Open\nLoews 51\nMcKesson Robbins 9\nMack Truck 22\nMont. Ward 35\nMurray Corp. 6%\nNash Kelvinator 11 Vi\nNat\u2019l. Biscuit 19\nNat\u2019l. Dairy 15 V*\nNat\u2019l. Pow. L. 9%\nN. Y. Central 19%\nNew Haven R. R. 2%\nNorth Am. 23 Vi\nPackard Motors 5%\nPenn. R. R. 22%\nPullman Co. 31%\nRadio 7%\nRep. Iron Steel 18 V*\nSears-Roebuck 55\nSouth Pac. 21\nStandard Brands 9\nS. O. of N. J. 45%\nSocony-Vacum. 15 V*\nStewart-Wamer 10%\nStudebaker 6%\nTexas Corp. 39%\nTexas Gulf 29%\nUnion Carbide. 72\nUnion Pacific 88\nUnited Air.. 19%\nUnite